# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: euler-tour-technique
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] A version of depth-first search was investigated in the 19th century by French mathematician Charles Pierre Trémaux as a strategy for solving mazes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] The time and space analysis of DFS differs according to its application area.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] In theoretical computer science, DFS is typically used to traverse an entire graph, and takes time $O(|V|+|E|)$ , where $|V|$ is the number of vertices and $|E|$ the number of edges.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] This is linear in the size of the graph.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] In these applications it also uses space $O(|V|)$ in the worst case to store the stack of vertices on the current search path as well as the set of already-visited vertices.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Thus, in this setting, the time and space bounds are the same as for breadth-first search and the choice of which of these two algorithms to use depends less on their complexity and more on the different properties of the vertex orderings the two algorithms produce.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] For applications of DFS in relation to specific domains, such as searching for solutions in artificial intelligence or web-crawling, the graph to be traversed is often either too large to visit in its entirety or infinite (DFS may suffer from non-termination).
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] In such cases, search is only performed to a limited depth; due to limited resources, such as memory or disk space, one typically does not use data structures to keep track of the set of all previously visited vertices.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] For such applications, DFS also lends itself much better to heuristic methods for choosing a likely-looking branch.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] When an appropriate depth limit is not known a priori, iterative deepening depth-first search applies DFS repeatedly with a sequence of increasing limits.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] In the artificial intelligence mode of analysis, with a branching factor greater than one, iterative deepening increases the running time by only a constant factor over the case in which the correct depth limit is known due to the geometric growth of the number of nodes per level.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] DFS may also be used to collect a sample of graph nodes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] However, incomplete DFS, similarly to incomplete BFS, is biased towards nodes of high degree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] The edges traversed in this search form a Trémaux tree, a structure with important applications in graph theory.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Performing the same search without remembering previously visited nodes results in visiting the nodes in the order A, B, D, F, E, A, B, D, F, E, etc. forever, caught in the A, B, D, F, E cycle and never reaching C or G.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Iterative deepening is one technique to avoid this infinite loop and would reach all nodes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] The result of a depth-first search of a graph can be conveniently described in terms of a spanning tree of the vertices reached during the search.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Based on this spanning tree, the edges of the original graph can be divided into three classes: **forward edges**, which point from a node of the tree to one of its descendants, **back edges**, which point from a node to one of its ancestors, and **cross edges**, which do neither.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Sometimes **tree edges**, edges which belong to the spanning tree itself, are classified separately from forward edges.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] If the original graph is undirected then all of its edges are tree edges or back edges.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] It is also possible to use depth-first search to linearly order the vertices of a graph or tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] For binary trees there is additionally **in-ordering** and **reverse in-ordering**.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] For example, when searching the directed graph below beginning at node A, the sequence of traversals is either A B D B A C A or A C D C A B A (choosing to first visit B or C from A is up to the algorithm).
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Note that repeat visits in the form of backtracking to a node, to check if it has still unvisited neighbors, are included here (even if it is found to have none).
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Thus the possible preorderings are A B D C and A C D B, while the possible postorderings are D B C A and D C B A, and the possible reverse postorderings are A C B D and A B C D.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Reverse postordering produces a topological sorting of any directed acyclic graph.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] This ordering is also useful in control-flow analysis as it often represents a natural linearization of the control flows.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] The graph above might represent the flow of control in the code fragment below, and it is natural to consider this code in the order A B C D or A C B D but not natural to use the order A B D C or A C D B.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] The recursive implementation will visit the nodes from the example graph in the following order: A, B, D, F, E, C, G.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] The non-recursive implementation will visit the nodes as: A, E, F, B, D, C, G.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] 2. it delays checking whether a vertex has been discovered until the vertex is popped from the stack rather than making this check before adding the vertex.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] If G is a tree, replacing the queue of the breadth-first search algorithm with a stack will yield a depth-first search algorithm.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] For general graphs, replacing the stack of the iterative depth-first search implementation with a queue would also produce a breadth-first search algorithm, although a somewhat nonstandard one.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] Another possible implementation of iterative depth-first search uses a stack of iterators of the list of neighbors of a node, instead of a stack of nodes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] This yields the same traversal as recursive DFS.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] The computational complexity of DFS was investigated by John Reif.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] More precisely, given a graph G , let $O=(v_{1},\dots ,v_{n})$ be the ordering computed by the standard recursive DFS algorithm.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] This ordering is called the lexicographic depth-first search ordering.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] John Reif considered the complexity of computing the lexicographic depth-first search ordering, given a graph and a source.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] A decision version of the problem (testing whether some vertex u occurs before some vertex v in this order) is **P**-complete, meaning that it is "a nightmare for parallel processing".
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] A depth-first search ordering (not necessarily the lexicographic one), can be computed by a randomized parallel algorithm in the complexity class RNC.
[src:euler-tour-technique/depth-first-search] As of 1997, it remained unknown whether a depth-first traversal could be constructed by a deterministic parallel algorithm, in the complexity class NC.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] The **Euler tour technique** (**ETT**), named after Leonhard Euler, is a method in graph theory for representing trees.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] The tree is viewed as a directed graph that contains two directed edges for each edge in the tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] The tree can then be represented as a Eulerian circuit of the directed graph, known as the **Euler tour representation** (**ETR**) of the tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] The ETT allows for efficient, parallel computation of solutions to common problems in algorithmic graph theory.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] It was introduced by Tarjan and Vishkin in 1984.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] The resulting list *succ* will be circular.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] The overall construction takes work *W*(*n*) = O(sort(*n*)) (the time it takes to sort *n* items in parallel) if the tree has *n* nodes, as in trees the number of edges is one less than the number of nodes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] If the tree has a root, we can split the circular list *succ* at that root.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] In that case, we can speak of *advance* and *retreat* edges: given a pair of nodes *u*,*v*, the first occurrence of either (*u*,*v*) or (*v*,*u*) in the ETR is called the *advance edge*, and the second occurrence is called the *retreat edge*.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] This appeals to the intuition that the first time such an edge is traversed the distance to the root is increased, while the second time the distance decreases.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] Rerooting the tree can be done in constant time O(1) by splitting the circular list *succ* at the new root.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] Determine the level of each node: Do a prefix sum on the ETR, where every advance edge counts as 1, and every retreat edge counts as −1.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] Then the value at the advance edge (*u*,*v*) is the level of *v*.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] Number of nodes in a subtree rooted at *v*: assume the parent of v is u, determine advance edge (*u*,*v*), and the retreat edge (*v*,*u*) in parallel, and then count the number of advance edges between (*u*,*v*) and (*v*,*u*) using prefix sum.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] The depth-first search index of a node *v*: count the number of advance edges up to and including (*u*,*v*).
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] Determine the lowest common ancestor of two nodes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] Henzinger and King suggest to represent a given tree by keeping its Euler tour in a balanced binary search tree, keyed by the index in the tour.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] So for example, the unbalanced tree in the example above, having 7 nodes, will be represented by a balanced binary tree with 14 nodes, one for each time each node appears on the tour.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] We can represent a forest (an acyclic graph) using a collection of ET trees - one ET tree for one forest tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] This representation allows us to quickly answer the question "what is the root of node v?" by just moving to the first node of the ET tree (since nodes in the ET tree are keyed by their location in the Euler tour, and the root is the first and last node in the tour).
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] When the represented forest is updated (e.g. by connecting two trees to a single tree or by splitting a tree to two trees), the corresponding Euler-tour structure can be updated in time O(log(n)).
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] Link/cut trees have similar performance guarantees.
[src:euler-tour-technique/euler-tour-technique] While LC trees are good for maintaining aggregates on paths of a tree (making it a good choice data structure in network flow algorithms), ET trees are better at keeping aggregate information on subtrees.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A **Fenwick tree** or **binary indexed tree** **(BIT)** is a data structure that stores an array of values and can efficiently compute prefix sums of the values *and* update the values.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] It also supports an efficient rank-search operation for finding the longest prefix whose sum is no more than a specified value.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Its primary use is operating on the cumulative distribution function of a statistical frequency table which is updated often.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] This structure was proposed by Boris Ryabko in 1989 with a further modification published in 1992.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] It has subsequently become known under the name Fenwick tree after Peter Fenwick, who described this structure in his 1994 article.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A simple array of values is trivial (constant-time) to update but requires $O(n)$ time to compute a prefix sum or search for a prefix length.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] An array of prefix sums can return a prefix sum in constant time, and search for a prefix length in $O(\log n)$ time, but requires $O(n)$ time to update one of the values.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree allows all three operations to be performed in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] This is achieved by representing the values as a tree with $n+1$ nodes where each node in the tree stores the sum of the values from the index of its parent (exclusive) up to the index of the node (inclusive).
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The tree itself is implicit and can be stored as an array of n values, with the implicit root node omitted from the array.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The tree structure allows the operations of value retrieval, value update, prefix sum, and range sum to be performed using only $O(\log n)$ node accesses.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Given an array of values, it is sometimes desirable to calculate the running total of values up to each index according to some associative binary operation (addition on integers being by far the most common).
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Fenwick trees provide a method to query the running total at any index, or prefix sum, while allowing changes to the underlying value array and having all further queries reflect those changes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Fenwick trees are particularly designed to implement adaptive arithmetic coding, which maintains counts of each symbol produced and needs to convert those to the cumulative probability of a symbol less than a given symbol.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Development of operations it supports were primarily motivated by use in that case.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree is an implicit tree where nodes are consecutively numbered, and parent-child relationships are determined by arithmetic on the node indexes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] An important function in this index arithmetic is the *least significant set bit*.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] This is the greatest power of two which divides an index i .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] It can be efficiently computed in two's complement arithmetic as $\operatorname {lsb} (i)=i\mathbin {\&} -i$ (where & denotes bitwise AND).
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree is most easily understood using a one-based array $A[n]$ with n values.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Using half-open interval syntax, let $A(i,j]=\{A[k]\}_{k=i+1}^{j},$ the range from i (exclusive) to j (inclusive).
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The corresponding Fenwick array $F[n]$ stores the range sums $\textstyle F[i]=\sum A(i-\operatorname {lsb} (i),i]$ .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] That is, the sum of $\operatorname {lsb} (i)$ values ending with and including $A[i]$ .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A fictitious node 0 is used in some descriptions, but is never actually accessed and need not be explicitly stored. $\operatorname {lsb} (0)=\infty ,$ but the value is never actually needed. $F[0]$ may be considered to contain the sum of the empty range $A(0,0]=\{\}$ with value 0.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A "Fenwick tree" is actually *three* implicit trees over the same array: the *interrogation tree* used for translating indexes to prefix sums, the *update* tree used for updating elements, and the *search tree* for translating prefix sums to indexes (rank queries).
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The first two are normally walked upwards, while the third is usually walked downwards.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The interrogation tree is defined so that the parent of node i is $i-\operatorname {lsb} (i)=i\mathbin {\&} (i-1)$ .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Each level k of the tree contains nodes with indices corresponding to sums of k distinct powers of 2 (with $k=0$ representing an empty sum 0).
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] To find the prefix sum $A[1]+\cdots +A[i]$ , sum the values in i , its parent, its parent's parent, and so on up to (but not including) the root.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] To compute a range sum $A[i]+\cdots +A[j]$ , subtract the prefix sums for $i-1$ and j .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] This can be optimized by stopping at their first common ancestor.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] An extreme example is asking for a single entry $A[j]$ .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] In this case, the common ancestor of j and $i=j-1$ is $j-\operatorname {lsb} (j)$ , so start with $F[j]$ and then, as long as $i\neq j-\operatorname {lsb} (j)$ , subtract $F[i]$ and update `i := i - lsb(i)`.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The update tree is the mirror image of the interrogation tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The parent of node i is $i+\operatorname {lsb} (i)=(i\mathbin {|} (i-1))+1$ (where | denotes bitwise OR).
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] This conceptual tree is infinite, but only the part with indexes up to n is stored or used.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Excluding the fictitious nodes with indexes greater than n it will be a forest of disjoint trees, one for each bit set in the binary representation of n .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Here, a node's ancestors are all nodes whose range sums include its own.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] To modify one of the values $A[i]$ , add the change to $F[i]$ , then i 's parent, then its grandparent, and so on, until the index exceeds n .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Unlike the other two trees, the search tree is a binary tree, arranged in an order Knuth calls a "sideways heap".
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Each node is assigned a height equal to the number of trailing zeros in the binary representation of its index, with the parent and children being the numerically closest index(es) of the adjacent height.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Nodes with odd indexes ( $\operatorname {lsb} (i)=1$ ) are leaves.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Nodes with even indexes have the closest two nodes of the next-lowest index as children, $i\pm \operatorname {lsb} (i)/2$ .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Node i 's parent in the search tree is $(i-\operatorname {lsb} (i))\mathbin {|} (2\cdot \operatorname {lsb} (i))$ .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Although this tree is potentially infinite, we may define its root to be the highest *existing* node, whose index is the greatest power of 2 less than or equal to n .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] It is possible for a node to have a fictitious parent with an index greater than n yet still have an existing grandparent.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] If the example above applied to a 5-node tree, then node 5 would have a fictitious parent 6, but an existing grandparent 4.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The search tree may be considered a combination of the previous two trees.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A node's left subtree contains all of its descendants in the update tree, while its right subtree contains all of its descendants in the interrogation tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] A node's parent in the search tree is either its interrogation or update parent (depending on whether the node is a right or left child, respectively), and the other type of parent may be found by multiple upward steps in the search tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] However, upward traversals in the search tree are uncommon; its primary use is to perform rank queries: given a prefix sum, at what index does it appear?
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] This is done by a *downward* traversal through the search tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] During the traversal, three variables are maintained: The current node's index, the rank being sought in the subtree rooted at the current node, and a "fallback index" to be returned if the rank sought is greater than can be found in the subtree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Initially, the current node is the root, the rank sought is the original query, and the fallback index is a special "overflow" value indicating that the rank is not in the tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] Each step, either the current node is a fictitious node (index greater than n ), or we must decide if the position sought is to the left or right of the end of the current node.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] If the rank sought is less than the Fenwick array value $F[i]$ for the current node, we must search its left subtree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] If it is greater, search its right subtree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] If it is equal, the direction chosen depends on how you wish to handle searches for sums lying exactly between two nodes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] The function ${\text{lsb}}(n)$ computes the *least significant set bit* of the given n or, equivalently, the largest power of two that is also a divisor of n .
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] This function can be simply implemented in code through a bitwise AND operation: `lsb(n) = n & (-n)`, assuming two's complement negation.
[src:euler-tour-technique/fenwick-tree] One naïve algorithm to construct a Fenwick tree consists of initializing the tree with null values and updating each index individually.
[src:euler-tour-technique/list-ranking] In parallel algorithms, the **list ranking** problem involves determining the position, or rank, of each item in a linked list.
[src:euler-tour-technique/list-ranking] That is, the first item in the list should be assigned the number 1, the second item in the list should be assigned the number 2, etc.
[src:euler-tour-technique/list-ranking] Although it is straightforward to solve this problem efficiently on a sequential computer, by traversing the list in order, it is more complicated to solve in parallel.
[src:euler-tour-technique/list-ranking] As Anderson & Miller (1990) wrote, the problem was viewed as important in the parallel algorithms community both for its many applications and because solving it led to many important ideas that could be applied in parallel algorithms more generally.
[src:euler-tour-technique/list-ranking] The list ranking problem was posed by Wyllie (1979), who solved it with a parallel algorithm using logarithmic time and O(*n* log *n*) total steps (that is, O(*n*) processors).
[src:euler-tour-technique/list-ranking] This number of steps matches the sequential algorithm.
[src:euler-tour-technique/list-ranking] List ranking can equivalently be viewed as performing a prefix sum operation on the given list, in which the values to be summed are all equal to one.
[src:euler-tour-technique/list-ranking] For instance, the height of each node in the tree may be computed by an algorithm of this type in which the prefix sum adds 1 for each downward edge and subtracts 1 for each upward edge.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] In computer science, a **parallel algorithm**, as opposed to a traditional serial algorithm, is an algorithm which can do multiple operations in a given time.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] It has been a tradition of computer science to describe serial algorithms in abstract machine models, often the one known as random-access machine.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Similarly, many computer science researchers have used a so-called parallel random-access machine (PRAM) as a parallel abstract machine (shared-memory).
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Many parallel algorithms are executed concurrently – though in general concurrent algorithms are a distinct concept – and thus these concepts are often conflated, with which aspect of an algorithm is parallel and which is concurrent not being clearly distinguished.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Further, non-parallel, non-concurrent algorithms are often referred to as "sequential algorithms", by contrast with concurrent algorithms.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Algorithms vary significantly in how parallelizable they are, ranging from easily parallelizable to completely unparallelizable.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Further, a given problem may accommodate different algorithms, which may be more or less parallelizable.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Some problems are easy to divide up into pieces in this way – these are called *embarrassingly parallel problems.* Examples include many algorithms to solve Rubik's Cubes and find values which result in a given hash.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Some problems cannot be split up into parallel portions, as they require the results from a preceding step to effectively carry on with the next step – these are called **inherently serial problems**.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Examples include iterative numerical methods, such as Newton's method, iterative solutions to the three-body problem, and most of the available algorithms to compute pi (π).
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Some sequential algorithms can be converted into parallel algorithms using automatic parallelization.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] In many cases developing an effective parallel algorithm to solve a task requires developing new ideas and methods not needed in the design of a sequential algorithm to solve the same problem.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Examples of such cases include the practically important problems of searching for a target element in a data structure and the evaluation of an algebraic expression.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Parallel algorithms on individual devices have become more common since the early 2000s because of substantial improvements in multiprocessing systems and the rise of multi-core processors.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Up until the end of 2004, single-core processor performance rapidly increased via frequency scaling, and thus it was easier to construct a computer with a single fast core than one with many slower cores with the same throughput, so multicore systems were of more limited use.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Since 2004 however, frequency scaling hit a wall, and thus multicore systems have become more widespread, making parallel algorithms of more general use.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] The cost or complexity of serial algorithms is estimated in terms of the space (memory) and time (processor cycles) that they take.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Parallel algorithms need to optimize one more resource, the communication between different processors.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] There are two ways parallel processors communicate, shared memory or message passing.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Shared memory processing needs additional locking for the data, imposes the overhead of additional processor and bus cycles, and also serializes some portion of the algorithm.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Message passing processing uses channels and message boxes but this communication adds transfer overhead on the bus, additional memory need for queues and message boxes and latency in the messages.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Designs of parallel processors use special buses like crossbar so that the communication overhead will be small but it is the parallel algorithm that decides the volume of the traffic.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] If the communication overhead of additional processors outweighs the benefit of adding another processor, one encounters parallel slowdown.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Another problem with parallel algorithms is ensuring that they are suitably load balanced, by ensuring that *load* (overall work) is balanced, rather than input size being balanced.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] A subtype of parallel algorithms, *distributed algorithms*, are algorithms designed to work in cluster computing and distributed computing environments, where additional concerns beyond the scope of "classical" parallel algorithms need to be addressed.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Distributed algorithms are intended to run on a network of interconnected computers that communicate through shared memory or message passing.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Unlike traditional parallel algorithms, they must operate under additional constraints such as limited local knowledge, communication delays, the lack of a global state, and the possibility of node failures.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] The focus of distributed algorithms is on coordination problems that arise in distributed systems, including leader election, mutual exclusion, and consensus (computer science).
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] These problems are studied under different system models with varying assumptions, such as whether the system is synchronous or asynchronous and if there are failures, such as crash failures or Byzantine failures.
[src:euler-tour-technique/parallel-algorithm] Distributed algorithms have many practical applications in distributed databases, fault-tolerance systems, and large-scale networked applications.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] In computer science, **tree traversal** (also known as **tree search** and **walking the tree**) is a form of graph traversal and refers to the process of visiting (e.g. retrieving, updating, or deleting) each node in a tree data structure exactly once.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Such traversals are classified by the order in which the nodes are visited.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] The following algorithms are described for a binary tree, but they may be generalized to other trees as well.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Unlike linked lists, one-dimensional arrays and other linear data structures, which are canonically traversed in linear order, trees may be traversed in multiple ways.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] They may be traversed in depth-first or breadth-first order.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] There are three common ways to traverse them in depth-first order: in-order, pre-order and post-order.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Beyond these basic traversals, various more complex or hybrid schemes are possible, such as depth-limited searches like iterative deepening depth-first search.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] The latter, as well as breadth-first search, can also be used to traverse infinite trees, see below.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Traversing a tree involves iterating over all nodes in some manner.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Because from a given node there is more than one possible next node (it is not a linear data structure), then, assuming sequential computation (not parallel), some nodes must be deferred—stored in some way for later visiting.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] This is often done via a stack (LIFO) or queue (FIFO).
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] As a tree is a self-referential (recursively defined) data structure, traversal can be defined by recursion or, more subtly, corecursion, in a natural and clear fashion; in these cases the deferred nodes are stored implicitly in the call stack.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Depth-first search is easily implemented via a stack, including recursively (via the call stack), while breadth-first search is easily implemented via a queue, including corecursively.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] In *depth-first search* (DFS), the search tree is deepened as much as possible before going to the next sibling.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Execute the following three operations in a certain order: N: Visit the current node.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] L: Recursively traverse the current node's left subtree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] R: Recursively traverse the current node's right subtree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] The trace of a traversal is called a sequentialisation of the tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] The traversal trace is a list of each visited node.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] No one sequentialisation according to pre-, in- or post-order describes the underlying tree uniquely.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Given a tree with distinct elements, either pre-order or post-order paired with in-order is sufficient to describe the tree uniquely.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] However, pre-order with post-order leaves some ambiguity in the tree structure.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] There are three methods at which position of the traversal relative to the node (in the figure: red, green, or blue) the visit of the node shall take place.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] The choice of exactly one color determines exactly one visit of a node as described below.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's left subtree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's right subtree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] The pre-order traversal is a topologically sorted one, because a parent node is processed before any of its child nodes is done.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Visit the current node (in the figure: position blue).
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal can be useful to get postfix expression of a binary expression tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Visit the current node (in the figure: position green).
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] In a binary search tree ordered such that in each node the key is greater than all keys in its left subtree and less than all keys in its right subtree, in-order traversal retrieves the keys in *ascending* sorted order.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] In a binary search tree ordered such that in each node the key is greater than all keys in its left subtree and less than all keys in its right subtree, reverse in-order traversal retrieves the keys in *descending* sorted order.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for pre-order traversal.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for in-order traversal.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's last subtree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for post-order traversal.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Depending on the problem at hand, pre-order, post-order, and especially one of the number of subtrees − 1 in-order operations may be optional.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Also, in practice more than one of pre-order, post-order, and in-order operations may be required.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] For example, when inserting into a ternary tree, a pre-order operation is performed by comparing items.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] A post-order operation may be needed afterwards to re-balance the tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] In *breadth-first search* (BFS) or *level-order search*, the search tree is broadened as much as possible before going to the next depth.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] There are also tree traversal algorithms that classify as neither depth-first search nor breadth-first search.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] One such algorithm is Monte Carlo tree search, which concentrates on analyzing the most promising moves, basing the expansion of the search tree on random sampling of the search space.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Pre-order traversal can be used to make a prefix expression (Polish notation) from expression trees: traverse the expression tree pre-orderly.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] For example, traversing the depicted arithmetic expression in pre-order yields "+ * *A* − *B* *C* + *D* *E*".
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] In prefix notation, there is no need for any parentheses as long as each operator has a fixed number of operands.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Pre-order traversal is also used to create a copy of the tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal can generate a postfix representation (Reverse Polish notation) of a binary tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Traversing the depicted arithmetic expression in post-order yields "*A* *B* *C* − * *D* *E* + +"; the latter can easily be transformed into machine code to evaluate the expression by a stack machine.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal is also used to delete the tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Each node is freed after freeing its children.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] In-order traversal is very commonly used on binary search trees because it returns values from the underlying set in order, according to the comparator that set up the binary search tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Below are examples of stack-based implementation for pre-order, post-order and in-order traversal in recursive approach (left) as well as iterative approach (right).
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Implementations in iterative approach are able to avoid the drawbacks of recursion, particularly limitations of stack space and performance issues.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Several alternative implementations are also mentioned.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] The `node` to be started with may have been found in the binary search tree `bst` by means of a standard **search** function, which is shown here in an implementation without parent pointers, i.e. it uses a `stack` for holding the ancestor pointers.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Note that the function does not use keys, which means that the sequential structure is completely recorded by the binary search tree’s edges.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] For traversals without change of direction, the (amortised) average complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(1),$ because a full traversal takes $2n-2$ steps for a BST of size $n,$ 1 step for edge up and 1 for edge down.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] The worst-case complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(h)$ with h as the height of the tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] All the above implementations require stack space proportional to the height of the tree which is a call stack for the recursive and a parent (ancestor) stack for the iterative ones.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] In a poorly balanced tree, this can be considerable.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] With the iterative implementations we can remove the stack requirement by maintaining parent pointers in each node, or by threading the tree (next section).
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] A binary tree is threaded by making every left child pointer (that would otherwise be null) point to the in-order predecessor of the node (if it exists) and every right child pointer (that would otherwise be null) point to the in-order successor of the node (if it exists).
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] We can make only one traversal at a time.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] It is more prone to errors when both the children are not present and both values of nodes point to their ancestors.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Revert the changes to restore original tree.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Also, listed below is pseudocode for a simple queue based level-order traversal, and will require space proportional to the maximum number of nodes at a given depth.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] This can be as much as half the total number of nodes.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] A more space-efficient approach for this type of traversal can be implemented using an iterative deepening depth-first search.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] While traversal is usually done for trees with a finite number of nodes (and hence finite depth and finite branching factor) it can also be done for infinite trees.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] This is of particular interest in functional programming (particularly with lazy evaluation), as infinite data structures can often be easily defined and worked with, though they are not (strictly) evaluated, as this would take infinite time.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Some finite trees are too large to represent explicitly, such as the game tree for chess or Go, and so it is useful to analyze them as if they were infinite.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] A basic requirement for traversal is to visit every node eventually.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] For infinite trees, simple algorithms often fail this.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] For example, given a binary tree of infinite depth, a depth-first search will go down one side (by convention the left side) of the tree, never visiting the rest, and indeed an in-order or post-order traversal will never visit *any* nodes, as it has not reached a leaf (and in fact never will).
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] By contrast, a breadth-first (level-order) traversal will traverse a binary tree of infinite depth without problem, and indeed will traverse any tree with bounded branching factor.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] By contrast, a breadth-first search will never reach the grandchildren, as it seeks to exhaust the children first.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] A more sophisticated analysis of running time can be given via infinite ordinal numbers; for example, the breadth-first search of the depth 2 tree above will take ω·2 steps: ω for the first level, and then another ω for the second level.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Thus, simple depth-first or breadth-first searches do not traverse every infinite tree, and are not efficient on very large trees.
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] However, hybrid methods can traverse any (countably) infinite tree, essentially via a diagonal argument ("diagonal"—a combination of vertical and horizontal—corresponds to a combination of depth and breadth).
[src:euler-tour-technique/tree-traversal] Concretely, given the infinitely branching tree of infinite depth, label the root (), the children of the root (1), (2), ..., the grandchildren (1, 1), (1, 2), ..., (2, 1), (2, 2), ..., and so on.
